<center><h1>ICOSAHEDRON</h1><br><img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~c=
ass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/pictures/icosahedron.JPG">
  <br>See the icosahedron rotating around the <a href=3D"https://personal.m=
ath.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/ps/icosahedron-x.ps"=
>x</a>,=20
  <a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchan=
g/webpages/ps/icosahedron-y.ps">y</a>, <a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc=
.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/ps/icosahedron-z.ps">z</a> =
axis.</center>
<table cellpadding=3D"20">
<tbody><tr><td><h7><b>Properties of the Icosahedron</b></h7></td></tr>
<tr><td><li>Faces: 20 triangles</li><li>Vertices: 12, each with 5 edges mee=
ting
  </li><li>Edges: 30</li><li>Dihedral angle: 138=B011'</li></td></tr>

<tr><td><h7><b>The Symmetry</b></h7></td></tr>
<tr><td><a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects=
/cchang/webpages/ps/ico-sym.ps"><img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~c=
ass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/pictures/ico-sym.JPG"></a></td></=
tr>

<tr><td><h7><b>Surface Area</b></h7></td></tr>
<tr><td><a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects=
/cchang/webpages/ps/ico-face.ps"><img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~=
cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/pictures/ico-face.JPG"></a><br>
  The surface area of an icosahedron is made up of 20 regular triangles.</t=
d></tr>

<tr><td><h7><b>Volume</b></h7></td></tr>
<tr><td>One way of calculating the volume: the octahedron can be divided in=
to 20 tetrahedra.<br>
  Each can be calculated using the pyramid method.<br>
  To get the vertices, take a look at this picture:<br>
  <a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchan=
g/webpages/ps/ico-in-octa.ps"><img src=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cas=
s/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/pictures/ico-in-octa.JPG"></a><br>
  Each vertex of the icosahedron lies on the edge of octahedron,<br>
  is divided into 2 lines with the golden mean ratio =D8.<br>
  Another way to calculate the volume is divide the icosahedron into 3 part=
s.<br>
  The top part: <a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/=
projects/cchang/webpages/ps/ico-pyramid.ps"><img src=3D"https://personal.ma=
th.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/pictures/ico-pyramid.=
JPG"></a><br>
  The angle between the two red lines on the pentagon is 360/5=3D72=B0.
  Let r =3D radius of the pentagon, a =3D length of edge, by the cosine law=
:<br>
  a=B2 =3D r=B2 + r =B2 - 2r=B2cos(72=B0)<br>
  The height of the pyramid is calculated by the Pythagoras theorem. h=B2 =
=3D r=B2 + a=B2.<br>
  The bottom part of the icosahedron is the same.<br>
  The top view of the middle piece: <a href=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca=
/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpages/ps/ico-pentagon.ps"><img src=
=3D"https://personal.math.ubc.ca/~cass/courses/m308/projects/cchang/webpage=
s/pictures/ico-pentagon.JPG"></a><br>
  V =3D [5 =D7 (3 + &#8730;5) / 12]a=B3
  </td></tr>


</tbody></table></body></html>
